Intellectual merits: The NSF major research instrument development program supported the successful installation and modification of a Hitachi H9500 80-300kV environmental transmission electron microscope (ETEM) for dynamic ETEM with following capabilities: fast electron imaging and diffraction under gas or liquid environments, low dose, single electron detection, imaging of soft and radiation sensitive materials, and direct optical access to sample and electron photocathode through custom built optical ports and extension of the TEM column. A 10-ns laser was acquired under the NSF support for the study of laser-matter interaction. Additional university funding enabled the purchase and installation of an electrochemical liquid cell holder. The instrument now enables the study of a broad range of research topics at the forefront of Chemistry, Physics, and Materials Science, including

Chemical reaction and rapid phase changes of supported nanoparticles;
The kinetics of the oxygen reduction reaction in electrochemical energy conversion;
The dynamics of ferroelectric domain switching and charge and orbital ordering in complex oxides;
Nucleation and growth of nanowires;
Degradation mechanisms in lithium-ion batteries;
Assembly and alignment of synthetic molecular peptides in self-assembled nanostructured materials;
Cellular internalization of nanoparticles by cancer cells and interactions of nanomedicine and cells.


Moreover the study of native peptides and cells is facilitated through the use of liquid cells and the direct electron detection CMOS sensor which enables low electron dose, in vivo, electron imaging.

Broad impacts: The development of dynamic environmental transmission electron microscope opens up broad new areas of materials research to researchers at the University of Illinois as well as to the scientific community as a whole. While environmental TEMs are widely employed for studying of chemical reactions and nanostructure growth here in USA and worldwide, the facility we developed here is unique in the country. The instrument now is maintained and operated by staff scientists in the Center for Microanalysis of Materials, which is an open access facility with dedicated staff that serves more than 850 users from over a 100 research groups across 30 departments at Illinois as well as researchers from other institutions throughout the nation. The shared instrumentation facilitates the "hands-on" training of a large number of graduate students and professional scientists from all over the world. The shared instrumentation is also an important resource for REU programs

Specifically, the development of DETEM now enables graduate student research programs from departments of materials science, chemical engineering, chemistry, mechanical engineering and nuclear science and collaborative research with multiple institutions that have revealed new mechanisms of high temperature oxidation, nanoparticle transformation, catalyst reforming and liquid phase colloidal assembly.



